    body: `For fifteen years we have done one thing: help a person see themselves clearly enough to choose well. The tools have changed. The work has not. So when people ask whether artificial intelligence will replace career counselling, the honest answer is that it will replace parts of it, improve other parts, and leave the most important part untouched.

It helps to separate the work into two kinds. There is the work of measurement and pattern — gathering data, scoring it, comparing it against what is known. And there is the work of judgement and meaning — sitting with a person as they decide what kind of life they want, and what they are prepared to give up for it. AI is already good at the first. It is structurally unsuited to the second.

## What should be automated

Scoring and consistency. A well-designed psychometric instrument — aptitude, interest along RIASEC lines, personality along the Big Five — is more accurate when scored by machine than by hand. Software does not tire on the four-hundredth report, does not round generously for a likeable student, does not forget a sub-scale. Automation removes the small human errors that creep into repetitive measurement, and that is a genuine gain.

Breadth of information. No counsellor can hold every entrance route, every cut-off, every emerging role in their head. The sheer volume of pathways has outgrown memory. AI is well suited to retrieving, organising and keeping this current. Used this way, it widens the set of options a student is even aware of — which is often where the real failure of guidance begins.

First drafts and admin. Summarising a report, preparing a comparison of three colleges, drafting a statement of purpose for the student to then rewrite in their own voice, scheduling, reminders — removing this frees the counsellor to spend the hour on the person rather than the paperwork.

## What must stay human

Interpretation in context. A score is a sentence, not a verdict. The same aptitude profile means something different for a student who is the first in the family to finish school than for one with three engineers at the dinner table. Context, constraint and family expectation are not noise to be corrected for. They are the actual problem, and reading them requires a person.

The conversation about meaning. A test can tell you what you are good at. It cannot tell you what you are willing to suffer for. Career choices are rarely limited by ability; they are limited by fear, by money, by the quiet pressure to not disappoint. Surfacing that, gently, and helping someone separate their own voice from the voices around them — this is counselling, and it cannot be automated, because it depends on trust between two people.

Accountability. When a young person commits years to a path, someone must own the recommendation and stand behind it. A model cannot be accountable. It cannot notice that a student went quiet when a particular option came up, then follow that silence to what it conceals.

## The honest shape of it

The right design is not human versus machine. It is the machine doing the measuring, retrieving and drafting so well that the human is free to do the part only a human can: judgement, meaning and care. A counsellor armed with good instruments and good information is better than one without. A student handed only a generated report, with no one to interpret it, has been given data and called it guidance.

That is the line we hold. Automate the measurement. Keep the meaning human. The science earns the trust; the conversation is where the decision is actually made.`,
