    body: `Most people who come to career counselling are not short of information. They arrive having already read the course lists, the eligibility rules, the salary ranges, the cut-offs. A student deciding after the 10th can recite the streams. A professional thinking about a switch knows, roughly, what each path pays.

So if the information is already there, what is left to change? The answer is the thing the information never produces on its own: a decision.

## Information is abundant. Decisions are scarce.

Information is symmetrical. Everyone reading the same article gets the same facts. That is its strength and its limit. A brochure tells you what a course contains; it does not tell you whether it is a good fit for you. A salary figure describes a market; it does not describe your tolerance for the work that earns it. The web is excellent at answering "what exists." It is silent on "what should I do, given who I am."

A decision is asymmetrical. It depends on facts that are specific to one person — aptitude, interests, temperament, constraints, what they are willing to trade away. Two students with identical marks should often make different choices. Information cannot tell them apart. A decision must.

## What actually gets in the way

When a capable person stays stuck despite knowing the options, the obstacle is rarely missing information. It is usually one of a few familiar things.

Too many options, weighted equally. Fifteen plausible paths feel worse than three, because the mind cannot compare fifteen things at once. Without a way to rank them against what matters, every option looks defensible and none feels chosen.

Other people's voices standing in for your own. A stream picked because a cousin did well in it. A safe degree chosen to settle a parent's anxiety. Good counselling separates these out, so the person can see which preferences are theirs.

Confusing interest with aptitude, and both with the job. Liking a subject, being good at it, and enjoying the daily work it leads to are three different things. Many regretted choices come from collapsing them into one.

## What counselling adds

It measures what the person cannot see in themselves. Well-built psychometrics give an outside reading of strengths and inclinations that self-assessment tends to distort. People routinely over-rate what they enjoy and under-rate what they are quietly good at.

It narrows honestly. The point is not to hand back a longer list. It is to reduce a wide field to a small set of options that genuinely fit, and to be clear about why the others were set aside.

It surfaces trade-offs instead of hiding them. Every real path costs something — years, money, geography, the roads not taken. A decision made with the trade-offs in view is one a person can stand behind later, even when it gets hard.

## The real outcome

The output of good counselling is not a report. It is a person who can explain their own decision — what they chose, what they declined, and why. That explanation is what holds up months later, when the novelty has worn off and the work is just work.`,
