    body: `For a large share of Indian students, the months after class 12 collapse into two letters: JEE or NEET. Engineering or medicine. The coaching is built for it, the dinner-table conversations assume it, and the question "what next?" quietly becomes "which of the two?" The trouble is not that engineering and medicine are poor choices. For some students they are exactly right. The trouble is that a binary is being treated as a map, when it is closer to two roads on a continent.

## Why the binary persists

The binary survives for understandable reasons. Both paths are legible: parents recognise the degree, the exam, the rough salary. Both have visible role models nearby. And both have an enormous coaching industry whose business depends on the funnel staying narrow. None of this makes them the best fit for any particular person. It makes them the most repeated.

## The map is wider than two roads

Step back and the actual terrain is broad. After class 12 a student can enter, among many others: the pure and applied sciences, where research and analytics careers begin; economics, increasingly quantitative and a strong feeder into finance, policy and data; commerce and finance proper, including the CA, CS and CMA professional routes; design across product, communication and fashion, entered through NID, NIFT and UCEED rather than JEE; architecture and planning; law, now a five-year integrated degree taken straight after school via CLAT; psychology and the wider social sciences; computer applications and data fields that do not require an engineering seat; hospitality and culinary arts; agriculture and allied health sciences such as physiotherapy, nutrition and nursing; and the liberal arts, which remain a serious foundation for writing, research, civil services and management.

This is not an exotic list. Every item on it is an established profession with employers, salaries and progression.

## Beyond degrees: domains and routes

A second mistake is to think only in degrees. Domains are the worlds a person eventually works inside: healthcare, climate and energy, public policy, media, manufacturing, financial services, education. The same degree can open several domains; the same domain can be entered through several degrees. Routes are the shapes a path can take: a single-honours degree, an interdisciplinary degree, a professional qualification taken alongside graduation, a diploma followed by lateral entry, or undergraduate study abroad. Most students are shown one route when in practice the route is a choice in its own right.

## How to read the wider map

The point is better matching, not more options. First, work from the person, not the exam. Established psychometrics give a usable starting frame: broad personality traits, interest patterns of the kind RIASEC describes, and genuine aptitudes measured rather than assumed. A student strong in spatial reasoning and visual thinking, indifferent to memorising biology, is being poorly served by being pushed at NEET. That is information, not failure.

Second, read the labour market honestly. The aim is not to chase whatever sounds hot, but to choose work that fits the person and is likely to exist and pay reasonably over a working life. Third, keep options open where the cost is low. Early years that build durable capability leave more doors open than narrow specialisation chosen at seventeen under pressure.

A good decision after class 12 is not the one that sounds most impressive at a family gathering. It is the one a student can still stand behind ten years on, having seen the whole map before deciding which road to take.`,
