    pullQuote: "An assessment narrows the field of plausible choices. It does not choose for you.",
    body: `A good career assessment is not a verdict. It is a measurement — and like any measurement, it is useful only when you understand what it measures, how precisely, and where its limits lie. The instruments behind a serious assessment have been studied for decades. They are neither magic nor astrology. Read correctly, they sharpen a decision. Read carelessly, they manufacture false certainty.

Three families of measurement do most of the work: personality, interests, and aptitude. Each answers a different question.

## Personality: how you tend to operate

The most established model in psychology is the Big Five — five broad traits along which people vary: openness, conscientiousness, extraversion, agreeableness, and emotional stability. These are not types or boxes. They are continuous dimensions, and almost everyone sits somewhere in the middle of most of them.

Of the five, conscientiousness has the most consistent link to performance across a wide range of jobs, because diligence and follow-through travel everywhere. The rest matter more situationally. What personality cannot tell you is whether you will be good at a specific subject. A reserved person can be an excellent doctor. Traits describe probabilities, not destinies.

## Interests: where your attention goes willingly

The RIASEC model sorts interests into six themes — Realistic, Investigative, Artistic, Social, Enterprising, and Conventional. It maps what kinds of activities you are drawn to, not what you can do.

Interest predicts persistence. If the daily texture of a job bores you, talent rarely survives the years it takes to compound. But you cannot express interest in work you have never seen. That is why an assessment should widen your options, not just confirm the ones already in your head.

## Aptitude: what you can do, with effort

Aptitude tests measure specific reasoning abilities — verbal, numerical, spatial, abstract, mechanical. Of the three families, aptitude has the strongest relationship with how quickly someone learns demanding work. But aptitude is a snapshot of present ability, not a ceiling. A modest spatial score does not bar you from engineering; it tells you where you will have to work harder.

## What the science can and cannot do

Used together, these instruments triangulate. Where strong aptitude, real interest, and a fitting temperament overlap, you find directions worth taking seriously. Where they conflict, you find exactly the tensions worth talking through before you commit years and fees to a path.

It also has firm limits. No test measures motivation over a decade, family circumstances, the state of the job market, or the person you are still becoming. The numbers are the easy part. The work is interpretation. The right way to read your results is as evidence — not instruction. Look for convergence across the three families. Treat surprises as questions, not commands.`,
