    body: `The choice after class 10 feels larger than it is. Most students experience it as a single irreversible verdict. In practice it is a starting position, not a sentence. The aim is to make that position a considered one, so the decision can hold its shape when relatives, classmates, and well-meaning parents apply pressure in different directions.

## Separate the decision from the noise

The hardest part is rarely the subject matter. It is the volume around it. Before weighing options, name the voices out loud. Write down who is pushing for what, and what each person actually wants for you underneath the advice. Usually it reduces to two honest wishes: that you will be financially secure, and that you will not regret the choice. The specific stream they attach to those wishes is just their best guess, formed from their own era.

## Three inputs, in order

First, aptitude — your pattern of natural strengths, the way of thinking that feels less effortful for you than for others. It tells you where steady effort will compound fastest, and it is the input families most often skip.

Second, interest — what holds your attention when no one is grading you. Interest sustains the years of study a field demands. But a liking for hospital dramas is not an interest in physiology. Test interest against the actual daily work of a field, not its image.

Third, and last, opportunity — the labour market, family finances, available colleges. This matters, but it belongs third. When opportunity leads, students chase whichever field is loudly in demand today and arrive five years later to find the queue has moved.

## Clear away two myths

The first is that science is the "safe" superset that keeps all doors open. It does keep engineering and medical routes available, but carrying subjects you have no aptitude for has a cost in marks, confidence and time. The second is that commerce and arts are fallback streams. Commerce leads to chartered accountancy, economics, finance, law and management. The humanities lead to law, civil services, design, psychology and research. A stream chosen well beats a "prestigious" stream endured badly.

## A note on reversibility

Almost nothing here is permanent. Streams can be bridged, exams re-attempted, degrees switched. The students who struggle most are rarely those who picked the "wrong" stream. They are those who picked under pressure, stopped thinking, and never revisited the choice. Decide carefully, then hold the decision lightly.`,
